#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:96
msgid "Submitting Plugins to pytest-dev"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:98
msgid ""
"Pytest development of the core, some plugins and support code happens in "
"repositories living under the ``pytest-dev`` organisations:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:101
msgid "`pytest-dev on GitHub <https://github.com/pytest-dev>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:103
msgid "`pytest-dev on Bitbucket <https://bitbucket.org/pytest-dev>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:105
msgid ""
"All pytest-dev Contributors team members have write access to all contained "
"repositories.  Pytest core and plugins are generally developed using `pull "
"requests`_ to respective repositories."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:109
msgid "The objectives of the ``pytest-dev`` organisation are:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:111
msgid "Having a central location for popular pytest plugins"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:112
msgid ""
"Sharing some of the maintenance responsibility (in case a maintainer no "
"longer wishes to maintain a plugin)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:115
msgid ""
"You can submit your plugin by subscribing to the `pytest-dev mail list "
"<https://mail.python.org/mailman/listinfo/pytest-dev>`_ and writing a mail "
"pointing to your existing pytest plugin repository which must have the "
"following:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:120
msgid ""
"PyPI presence with a ``setup.py`` that contains a license, ``pytest-`` "
"prefixed name, version number, authors, short and long description."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:123
msgid ""
"a ``tox.ini`` for running tests using `tox <https://tox.readthedocs.io>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:125
msgid ""
"a ``README.txt`` describing how to use the plugin and on which platforms it "
"runs."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:128
msgid ""
"a ``LICENSE.txt`` file or equivalent containing the licensing information, "
"with matching info in ``setup.py``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:131
msgid "an issue tracker for bug reports and enhancement requests."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:133
msgid "a `changelog <http://keepachangelog.com/>`_"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:135
msgid ""
"If no contributor strongly objects and two agree, the repository can then be "
"transferred to the ``pytest-dev`` organisation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:138
msgid ""
"Here's a rundown of how a repository transfer usually proceeds (using a "
"repository named ``joedoe/pytest-xyz`` as example):"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:141
msgid ""
"``joedoe`` transfers repository ownership to ``pytest-dev`` administrator "
"``calvin``."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:142
msgid ""
"``calvin`` creates ``pytest-xyz-admin`` and ``pytest-xyz-developers`` teams, "
"inviting ``joedoe`` to both as **maintainer**."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:143
msgid ""
"``calvin`` transfers repository to ``pytest-dev`` and configures team access:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:145
msgid "``pytest-xyz-admin`` **admin** access;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:146
msgid "``pytest-xyz-developers`` **write** access;"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:148
msgid ""
"The ``pytest-dev/Contributors`` team has write access to all projects, and "
"every project administrator is in it. We recommend that each plugin has at "
"least three people who have the right to release to PyPI."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:152
msgid ""
"Repository owners can rest assured that no ``pytest-dev`` administrator will "
"ever make releases of your repository or take ownership in any way, except "
"in rare cases where someone becomes unresponsive after months of contact "
"attempts. As stated, the objective is to share maintenance and avoid "
"\"plugin-abandon\"."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:162
msgid "Preparing Pull Requests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:165
msgid "Short version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:167
msgid "Fork the repository."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:168
msgid ""
"Enable and install `pre-commit <https://pre-commit.com>`_ to ensure style-"
"guides and code checks are followed."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:169
msgid ""
"Follow **PEP-8** for naming and `black <https://github.com/psf/black>`_ for "
"formatting."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:170
msgid "Tests are run using ``tox``::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:172
msgid "tox -e linting,py37"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:174
msgid ""
"The test environments above are usually enough to cover most cases locally."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:176
msgid ""
"Write a ``changelog`` entry: ``changelog/2574.bugfix.rst``, use issue id "
"number and one of ``bugfix``, ``removal``, ``feature``, ``vendor``, ``doc`` "
"or ``trivial`` for the issue type."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:179
msgid ""
"Unless your change is a trivial or a documentation fix (e.g., a typo or "
"reword of a small section) please add yourself to the ``AUTHORS`` file, in "
"alphabetical order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:184
msgid "Long version"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:186
msgid ""
"What is a \"pull request\"?  It informs the project's core developers about "
"the changes you want to review and merge.  Pull requests are stored on "
"`GitHub servers <https://github.com/pytest-dev/pytest/pulls>`_. Once you "
"send a pull request, we can discuss its potential modifications and even add "
"more commits to it later on. There's an excellent tutorial on how Pull "
"Requests work in the `GitHub Help Center <https://help.github.com/articles/"
"using-pull-requests/>`_."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:194
msgid "Here is a simple overview, with pytest-specific bits:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:196
msgid ""
"Fork the `pytest GitHub repository <https://github.com/pytest-dev/"
"pytest>`__.  It's fine to use ``pytest`` as your fork repository name "
"because it will live under your user."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:201
msgid ""
"Clone your fork locally using `git <https://git-scm.com/>`_ and create a "
"branch::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:203
msgid ""
"$ git clone git@github.com:YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME/pytest.git\n"
"$ cd pytest\n"
"# now, create your own branch off \"master\":\n"
"\n"
"    $ git checkout -b your-bugfix-branch-name master"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:209
msgid ""
"Given we have \"major.minor.micro\" version numbers, bug fixes will usually "
"be released in micro releases whereas features will be released in minor "
"releases and incompatible changes in major releases."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:213
msgid ""
"If you need some help with Git, follow this quick start guide: https://git."
"wiki.kernel.org/index.php/QuickStart"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:216
msgid ""
"Install `pre-commit <https://pre-commit.com>`_ and its hook on the pytest "
"repo:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:218
msgid ""
"**Note: pre-commit must be installed as admin, as it will not function "
"otherwise**::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:220
msgid ""
"$ pip install --user pre-commit\n"
"$ pre-commit install"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:223
msgid "Afterwards ``pre-commit`` will run whenever you commit."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:225
msgid ""
"https://pre-commit.com/ is a framework for managing and maintaining multi-"
"language pre-commit hooks to ensure code-style and code formatting is "
"consistent."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:228
msgid "Install tox"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:230
msgid ""
"Tox is used to run all the tests and will automatically setup virtualenvs to "
"run the tests in. (will implicitly use http://www.virtualenv.org/en/"
"latest/)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:234
msgid "$ pip install tox"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:236
msgid "Run all the tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:238
msgid ""
"You need to have Python 3.7 available in your system.  Now running tests is "
"as simple as issuing this command::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:241
msgid "$ tox -e linting,py37"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:243
msgid ""
"This command will run tests via the \"tox\" tool against Python 3.7 and also "
"perform \"lint\" coding-style checks."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:246
msgid ""
"You can now edit your local working copy and run the tests again as "
"necessary. Please follow PEP-8 for naming."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:248
msgid ""
"You can pass different options to ``tox``. For example, to run tests on "
"Python 3.7 and pass options to pytest (e.g. enter pdb on failure) to pytest "
"you can do::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:251
msgid "$ tox -e py37 -- --pdb"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:253
msgid "Or to only run tests in a particular test module on Python 3.7::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:255
msgid "$ tox -e py37 -- testing/test_config.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:258
msgid "When committing, ``pre-commit`` will re-format the files if necessary."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:260
msgid ""
"If instead of using ``tox`` you prefer to run the tests directly, then we "
"suggest to create a virtual environment and use an editable install with the "
"``testing`` extra::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:263
msgid ""
"$ python3 -m venv .venv\n"
"$ source .venv/bin/activate  # Linux\n"
"$ .venv/Scripts/activate.bat  # Windows\n"
"$ pip install -e \".[testing]\""
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:268
msgid "Afterwards, you can edit the files and run pytest normally::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:270
msgid "$ pytest testing/test_config.py"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:273
msgid ""
"Commit and push once your tests pass and you are happy with your change(s)::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:275
msgid ""
"$ git commit -a -m \"<commit message>\"\n"
"$ git push -u"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:278
msgid ""
"Create a new changelog entry in ``changelog``. The file should be named "
"``<issueid>.<type>.rst``, where *issueid* is the number of the issue related "
"to the change and *type* is one of ``bugfix``, ``removal``, ``feature``, "
"``vendor``, ``doc`` or ``trivial``. You may not create a changelog entry if "
"the change doesn't affect the documented behaviour of Pytest."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:283
msgid ""
"Add yourself to ``AUTHORS`` file if not there yet, in alphabetical order."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:285
msgid ""
"Finally, submit a pull request through the GitHub website using this data::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:287
msgid ""
"head-fork: YOUR_GITHUB_USERNAME/pytest\n"
"compare: your-branch-name\n"
"\n"
"base-fork: pytest-dev/pytest\n"
"base: master"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:295
msgid "Writing Tests"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:297
msgid ""
"Writing tests for plugins or for pytest itself is often done using the "
"`testdir fixture <https://docs.pytest.org/en/latest/reference."
"html#testdir>`_, as a \"black-box\" test."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:299
msgid "For example, to ensure a simple test passes you can write:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:301
msgid ""
"def test_true_assertion(testdir):\n"
"    testdir.makepyfile(\n"
"        \"\"\"\n"
"        def test_foo():\n"
"            assert True\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    )\n"
"    result = testdir.runpytest()\n"
"    result.assert_outcomes(failed=0, passed=1)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:314
msgid ""
"Alternatively, it is possible to make checks based on the actual output of "
"the termal using *glob-like* expressions:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:317
msgid ""
"def test_true_assertion(testdir):\n"
"    testdir.makepyfile(\n"
"        \"\"\"\n"
"        def test_foo():\n"
"            assert False\n"
"    \"\"\"\n"
"    )\n"
"    result = testdir.runpytest()\n"
"    result.stdout.fnmatch_lines([\"*assert False*\", \"*1 failed*\"])"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:329
msgid ""
"When choosing a file where to write a new test, take a look at the existing "
"files and see if there's one file which looks like a good fit. For example, "
"a regression test about a bug in the ``--lf`` option should go into "
"``test_cacheprovider.py``, given that this option is implemented in "
"``cacheprovider.py``. If in doubt, go ahead and open a PR with your best "
"guess and we can discuss this over the code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:336
msgid "Joining the Development Team"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../CONTRIBUTING.rst:338
msgid ""
"Anyone who has successfully seen through a pull request which did not "
"require any extra work from the development team to merge will themselves "
"gain commit access if they so wish (if we forget to ask please send a "
"friendly reminder).  This does not mean your workflow to contribute changes, "
"everyone goes through the same pull-request-and-review process and no-one "
"merges their own pull requests unless already approved.  It does however "
"mean you can participate in the development process more fully since you can "
"merge pull requests from other contributors yourself after having reviewed "
"them."
msgstr ""
